# /etc/pam.d/tessera — STRICT mode (default).
#
# Tessera stack snippet. Include from a host PAM config like:
#     @include tessera
# in /etc/pam.d/sudo BEFORE the `pam_unix.so` line. The `required` control
# below means: USB cert auth MUST succeed; password fallback is denied.
# This is the safe default for production deployments where the operator
# has already issued tokens to every authorised user.
#
# To allow password fallback (e.g. during phased rollout) install
# `tessera-optional` instead — that file uses `sufficient` and falls
# through to pam_unix.so when the token is absent or fails.
#
# Account: required — denial here propagates regardless of subsequent
# modules.
#
# NOTE (0.3.12+): the `session` phase intentionally lives OUTSIDE this
# snippet. `pam_sm_open_session` of Tessera needs `XDG_SESSION_ID`
# pushed into the PAM environment by `pam_systemd.so` (delivered via
# `@include common-session` on Debian/Astra), and `common-session`
# almost always sits at the bottom of the host PAM file — i.e. AFTER
# wherever this snippet ends up included in the auth/account block.
# `integrate-pam.sh` therefore inserts an explicit
# `session required pam_tessera.so` line AFTER `@include common-session`
# instead of bundling it here. If you wire this snippet in by hand,
# remember to add that session line yourself.

auth        required     pam_tessera.so
account     required     pam_tessera.so
